The priests, however, had none of the characteristics which we are accustomed to asso— ciate with the word. They did not form an exclusive class or caste, nor did they require preliminary training or education. They were not excluded from other offices; on the contrary, the more important priesthoods were filled by the greatest states— men and generals—Julius Caesar was Pontifex Maximus while he was fighting in Gaul.
